The paper deals with game theory and optimization problems, which are typically categorized under cs.GT (Game Theory and Economics) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of strategies and approximation techniques suggests a focus on algorithms and data structures, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The mention of modeling practical contexts and stochastic winner-determination rules suggests a possible connection to machine learning and probabilistic methods, which could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.LG (Machine Learning).
